# Capacity Planning Tool — Cline Rules

## Design Philosophy

Every architectural rule in this file exists in service of one goal:
**clean architecture delivers consistent, unified appearance and behaviour across the app.**

Shortcuts are not free:
- An inline style means a colour that can't be themed from one place
- A raw hex value means a colour that doesn't update when the token changes
- A direct DOM mutation means a UI state Alpine doesn't know about
- A forgotten `syncStore()` call means a template that doesn't re-render
- A Tailwind utility class means a style outside the design token system

When in doubt, ask: *"does this decision make the app more or less consistent?"*
Prefer the choice that keeps control centralised and behaviour predictable.

---

## Known Issues & Improvement Backlog

Before starting any work, review **`docs/CODE_REVIEW.md`** for the current list of known
architectural issues, their severity, and the recommended execution order. Do not introduce
new instances of patterns already identified as debt in that document.

### CODE_REVIEW.md Maintenance

`docs/CODE_REVIEW.md` is the **live record of architectural debt and known issues**. It must be
kept current — a stale CODE_REVIEW.md is worse than none because it gives a false picture of the
codebase state.

**Rules (apply at the end of every task that touches architecture or fixes a known issue):**
- When a task **fixes** an issue listed in CODE_REVIEW.md: mark it resolved (with date and
  version) or remove it from the open issues list.
- When a task **discovers** a new architectural issue: add it to CODE_REVIEW.md before calling
  `attempt_completion`.
- When a task **partially addresses** an issue: update the description and note remaining work —
  do not mark it resolved until fully done.
- Do not complete a task that touches architecture without reading CODE_REVIEW.md first, to
  avoid re-introducing known debt.

**Scoped tasks — how to use CODE_REVIEW.md as your entry point:**
Rather than requesting a "full code review" in one task (which exhausts the context window),
start each task with:
1. Read `docs/CODE_REVIEW.md` to understand current debt state and priorities.
2. Read `.clinerules` for the architectural rules.
3. Select the **highest-priority open issue** (or the one explicitly requested).
4. Read only the files relevant to that concern.
   - If the task touches `css/design-tokens.css` or `css/styles.css`, also read
     `docs/DESIGN_SYSTEM.md` before writing any CSS (see CSS Architecture Standards below).
5. Fix, verify, update CODE_REVIEW.md, then call `attempt_completion`.

This keeps each task within context limits while still enabling cross-file reasoning on the
files that actually matter for the concern at hand.

---

## Project Overview
Alpine.js SPA — Phase 3 of a vanilla JS → Alpine.js migration, with Tailwind removed and a full
design-token CSS system added. Deployed as a static site on SharePoint. All logic lives in plain
`<script>` files loaded in a strict order. No build step, no bundler, no ES modules.

Current version: see `README.md` badge and `docs/CHANGELOG.md` for the latest.

## Tech Stack
- **Frontend**: Alpine.js v3 (reactivity + components), plain HTML5, CSS3
- **Charts**: Chart.js v4 (CDN, UMD build)
- **Storage**: Browser `localStorage` (abstracted via `js/storage.js`)
- **No build tools**: Direct browser execution — ES6+ syntax only, no transpilation
- **No ES modules**: `import`/`export` are **FORBIDDEN** (SharePoint CSP blocks them)
- **No Tailwind**: Removed in v1.4. Use semantic CSS classes in `css/styles.css` only.
- **No inline styles**: All presentational decisions must go through CSS classes or design tokens.

---

## File Architecture Map
Every file has **one** responsibility. Never blur these lines.

| File | Responsibility |
|------|----------------|
| `js/storage.js` | `localStorage` read/write abstraction. No Alpine, no DOM. |
| `js/data.js` | **Legacy mutable globals** (`employees`, `entries`, `months`, etc.). Migration target — do NOT add new globals here. |
| `js/store.js` | `Alpine.store('plan')`. Currently mirrors `data.js` globals (hybrid mode). The single source of truth for all Alpine templates. |
| `js/history.js` | Undo/redo stack. Currently vanilla globals (`undoStack`, `redoStack`). Migration target — move to store. |
| `js/chart.js` | Chart.js wrapper. Permitted to use `$refs` for canvas access. |
| `js/keyboard.js` | Global keyboard shortcuts **only**. Documented exception to the `addEventListener` rule. |
| `js/components.js` | All `Alpine.data()` component registrations. |
| `js/modals.js` | Modal open/close orchestration. **Known debt: still uses `innerHTML`.** Migration target. |
| `js/settings.js` | Settings page Alpine data and logic. |
| `js/app.js` | App initialisation — wires storage, data, store, and components together. |
| `css/design-tokens.css` | **Single source of truth** for all design tokens. |
| `css/styles.css` | Component styles only. Must reference `design-tokens.css` tokens. Contains a legacy `:root` block — see CSS debt below. |
| `index.html` | Main app page. |
| `settings.html` | Settings page. |
| `component-library.html` | Living component library. Must stay in sync with app components. |
| `docs/ARCHITECTURE.md` | **Human dev onboarding guide.** State flow, file responsibilities, Alpine patterns, CSS rules, SharePoint constraints. Read before touching any file. |
| `docs/CODE_REVIEW.md` | Live issue tracker — open debt, severity, status. AI consults before every task. |
| `docs/DESIGN_SYSTEM.md` | Design token and component class reference. Mirror of the CSS files. |

---

## Current Architecture State — Hybrid Mode
The app is mid-migration from vanilla JS to Alpine.js. **Read this before making any changes.**

### What "hybrid mode" means
- `data.js` still holds mutable globals (`employees`, `entries`, `planSettings`, etc.)
- `store.js` **mirrors** those globals into `Alpine.store('plan')` at init time
- After **every** mutation to a `data.js` global, `syncStore()` **must** be called to push the new
  values into the store so Alpine templates re-render
- This is intentional interim architecture, not a bug

### Rules for hybrid mode
- **Always call `syncStore()` after modifying** `employees`, `entries`, `months`, `activeLocations`,
  or `planSettings`
- **Never bypass `syncStore()`** by writing `Alpine.store('plan').x = value` directly — use the
  `data.js` mutation functions, then sync
- **Do not add new globals to `data.js`** — any brand-new state must go directly into
  `Alpine.store('plan')` as a store property
- The long-term goal is to eliminate `data.js` globals entirely, with `store.js` as sole state

### Known migration targets
Do not regress these. Migrate them when touching the relevant area:

| Target | Current State | Desired State |
|--------|--------------|---------------|
| `js/modals.js` | `innerHTML` template strings | Alpine modal component with `x-show`/`x-data` |
| `js/history.js` | `undoStack`/`redoStack` plain globals | Properties of `Alpine.store('plan')` |
| `js/data.js` | Mutable globals | Eliminated — state lives in store |
| `css/styles.css` `:root` block | Duplicate legacy tokens (see CSS debt below) | Removed; all usages replaced with `design-tokens.css` tokens |

