# Architecture & Code Quality Standards

## Alpine.js Coding Standards

The app uses Alpine.js for all reactivity. Vanilla JS DOM patterns are **FORBIDDEN** unless
explicitly documented as exceptions.

### FORBIDDEN patterns — never use these:
- `document.querySelector()` / `document.getElementById()` for UI interaction
- `element.classList.add/remove/toggle()` — use `:class` bindings instead
- `element.style.x = value` — use `:style` bindings instead
- `addEventListener()` for UI events on elements Alpine controls — use `x-on`/`@event` directives
- `window.xyz = function()` — attach to `Alpine.store()` or `Alpine.data()` instead
- `document.createElement()` / `innerHTML =` for rendering — use Alpine templates
- Adding new mutable globals to `data.js` — put new state in `Alpine.store('plan')` directly

### PERMITTED exceptions (comment the reason in the code):
- `addEventListener('keydown', ...)` for global keyboard shortcuts in `keyboard.js`
- Canvas/chart library initialisation that requires a DOM element (use `x-ref` to get it)
- `$nextTick` for operations that must occur after Alpine's DOM update
- Calls to `syncStore()` after `data.js` mutations (hybrid-mode requirement — see above)

### State management rules:
- All shared app state lives in `Alpine.store('plan')` (or named stores)
- Component-local state lives in `x-data` on that component's root element
- Modal state (which modal is open, its data) lives in the store — modals open/close reactively
- Undo/redo state **must** move to the store (currently a migration target — see above)

### syncStore() discipline:
- Every function that mutates `data.js` globals **must** end with a `syncStore()` call
- Do not call `syncStore()` more than once per logical operation (batch mutations, then sync once)
- Never call `syncStore()` inside a loop — batch the mutations, then call once after the loop

### Component patterns:
- Register all reusable components via `Alpine.data('componentName', () => ({...}))`
- Components communicate via the store or `$dispatch` custom events — never by calling each
  other's functions directly
- Use `x-ref` + `$refs` only when you genuinely need a DOM reference (e.g. focus management,
  canvas access)

### Modal pattern (target state — apply when migrating modals):
```html
<!-- Trigger -->
<button @click="$store.plan.openModal('empEdit', { empId: emp.id })">Edit</button>

<!-- Modal declaration (in component-library or page template) -->
<div role="dialog" aria-modal="true" aria-labelledby="modal-title-emp-edit"
     x-show="$store.plan.activeModal === 'empEdit'"
     x-data="empEditModal"
     @keydown.escape.window="$store.plan.closeModal()">
  ...
</div>
```
- Modal data (`empEditModal`) is an `Alpine.data()` component
- `activeModal` and `modalPayload` are store properties
- `openModal(name, payload)` and `closeModal()` are store methods

---

## CSS Architecture Standards

### Design token rules:
- **ALL** color values must use `var(--color-*)` tokens — never write raw hex, `rgb()`, or `rgba()`
  in `styles.css`
- **ALL** spacing values must use `var(--spacing-*)` tokens — never write raw `px` values
- **ALL** typography must use `var(--font-*)` tokens
- Z-index values must use `var(--z-*)` tokens
- Transitions must use `var(--duration-*)` and `var(--easing-*)` tokens
- When adding a new design decision (new color, new size), **add the token first**, then use it

### CSS token naming convention (use ONLY these prefixes):
| Prefix | Token file | Examples |
|--------|-----------|---------|
| `--color-*` | `design-tokens.css` | `--color-accent`, `--color-surface`, `--color-text-primary` |
| `--spacing-*` | `design-tokens.css` | `--spacing-xs`, `--spacing-sm`, `--spacing-md` |
| `--font-*` | `design-tokens.css` | `--font-size-sm`, `--font-weight-medium` |
| `--radius-*` | `design-tokens.css` | `--radius-sm`, `--radius-md` |
| `--shadow-*` | `design-tokens.css` | `--shadow-sm`, `--shadow-md` |
| `--z-*` | `design-tokens.css` | `--z-modal`, `--z-toast` |
| `--duration-*` | `design-tokens.css` | `--duration-fast`, `--duration-normal` |
| `--easing-*` | `design-tokens.css` | `--easing-standard` |

### Known CSS debt — legacy `:root` block in `styles.css`:
`styles.css` contains a legacy `:root` block with raw values (`--sap-blue`, `--gray-*`,
`--space-1`, `--color-bg`, etc.). These are **migration targets**:
- Do **not** add new custom properties to the `styles.css` `:root` block
- Do **not** use legacy variable names (`--space-1`, `--color-bg`, `--sap-blue`, etc.) in new rules
- When editing any CSS rule that currently references a legacy variable, migrate it to the
  corresponding `design-tokens.css` token at the same time
- Goal: remove the `styles.css` `:root` block entirely once all references are migrated

**Legacy → canonical token mapping (common cases):**
```
--sap-blue           →  --color-accent
--sap-blue-dark      →  --color-accent-hover
--sap-blue-light     →  --color-accent-subtle
--gray-50            →  --color-background
--gray-100           →  --color-surface-alt
--gray-200           →  --color-border
--gray-500           →  --color-text-muted
--gray-800           →  --color-text-primary
--color-bg           →  --color-background
--space-1            →  --spacing-xs
--space-2            →  --spacing-sm
--space-3            →  --spacing-md
--space-4            →  --spacing-lg
```

### DESIGN_SYSTEM.md — CSS authoring entry point

`docs/DESIGN_SYSTEM.md` is the **mirror of the CSS files** — it documents what exists in
`design-tokens.css` and `styles.css`. It is not a spec; the CSS files are the source of truth.

**Before editing `css/design-tokens.css` or `css/styles.css`:**
1. Read `docs/DESIGN_SYSTEM.md` to check whether a token or component pattern already covers
   what you need. Prefer reusing an existing token over introducing a new one.
2. Check the Color Palette section before adding any color token.
3. Check the Component Reference section before adding a new component class.

**After editing either CSS file — update `docs/DESIGN_SYSTEM.md` in the same task:**
- Added or changed a **design token** → update the relevant token table (Color Palette,
  Typography, Spacing, etc.).
- Added or changed a **component** → update the Component Reference section.
- Removed a token or component → remove it from the doc too.

Never add something to `DESIGN_SYSTEM.md` that isn't yet in the CSS.

### When adding any new token:
1. Add to `css/design-tokens.css` with the appropriate category prefix
2. Use the token in `css/styles.css`
3. Update `docs/DESIGN_SYSTEM.md` (the relevant token table)
4. Add the token to `component-library.html` token section if it's visible

### CSS naming convention:
- Component blocks: `.component-name` (e.g. `.modal`, `.btn`, `.data-table`)
- Component elements: `.component-name__element` (e.g. `.modal__header`, `.btn__icon`)
- Modifier variants: `.component-name--modifier` (e.g. `.btn--primary`, `.btn--sm`)
- State classes: `.is-active`, `.is-loading`, `.is-disabled`, `.has-error`
- Never use Tailwind utility classes — the project has removed Tailwind by design

### Interactive states required for every interactive element:
Every button, link, input, select, and clickable element **must** have explicit CSS for:
- `:hover` — visual feedback on mouse over
- `:focus-visible` — keyboard navigation indicator (do NOT remove outline, style it)
- `:active` — press feedback
- `:disabled` — muted/inert appearance + `cursor: not-allowed`

If any of these states are missing, the element is incomplete.

---

## HTML Structure Standards

### Semantic HTML requirements:
- Use `<main>` for the primary page content (one per page)
- Use `<header>`, `<nav>`, `<footer>` for structural regions
- Use `<section>` with `aria-labelledby` for major content regions
- Use `<button>` for interactive controls, `<a>` for navigation — never `<div>` or `<span>`
  with click handlers
- Tabular data **must** use `<table>`, `<th scope="col/row">`, `<caption>`

### Accessibility requirements:
- Every `<input>` must have an associated `<label>` (via `for`/`id` or `aria-label`)
- Icon-only buttons must have `aria-label`
- Modals must have `role="dialog"`, `aria-modal="true"`, `aria-labelledby` pointing to the modal title
- When a modal opens, focus **must** move to the first interactive element inside it
- Toast/status messages must use `aria-live="polite"` (or `role="status"`)
- Collapsible sections must have `aria-expanded` on the trigger

### Script loading order (all HTML pages must follow this exactly):
```html
<!-- 1. CSS: tokens first, then component styles -->
<link rel="stylesheet" href="css/design-tokens.css">
<link rel="stylesheet" href="css/styles.css">

<!-- 2. Third-party non-Alpine libs (Chart.js, etc.) -->
<script src="...chart.js..."></script>

<!-- 3. Alpine plugins (Focus, Mask, etc.) — BEFORE Alpine core -->
<!-- <script src="...alpine-focus..."></script> -->

<!-- 4. App modules — in strict dependency order -->
<script src="js/storage.js"></script>
<script src="js/countries.js"></script>
<script src="js/data.js"></script>
<script src="js/history.js"></script>
<script src="js/chart.js"></script>
<script src="js/keyboard.js"></script>
<script src="js/components.js"></script>
<script src="js/modals.js"></script>
<script src="js/settings.js"></script>
<script src="js/store.js"></script>
<script src="js/app.js"></script>

<!-- 5. Alpine core — LAST, with defer -->
<script defer src="...alpinejs..."></script>
```
Any deviation causes silent Alpine initialisation failures. **CSS links must come before all
`<script>` tags.**

---

## Cross-Page Consistency

When adding a feature, check **all** pages it affects:
- `index.html` — main app
- `settings.html` — settings
- `component-library.html` — must be updated if components change

The `<head>` section (meta tags, CSS links, script tags) **must be identical** across all app pages.
If you update one page's `<head>`, update all pages.

---

## Component Library Maintenance

- When creating or modifying a component, update `component-library.html` in the same task
- The library must show **all** interactive states for every component
- The library header must show the current app version and "last updated" date
- If a component in the library no longer matches the app, it is a bug — fix the library or the app

---

## Alpine + SharePoint Compatibility

- No ES module imports (`import`/`export`) — SharePoint's CSP may block them
- No build step — all JS must be plain scripts loadable directly
- Alpine and any plugins should have a local fallback copy alongside the CDN link
- Test all pointer events — SharePoint's injected CSS can override cursor styles
- Avoid `position: fixed` for full-page overlays — SharePoint's chrome interferes
- Avoid `vh` units — SharePoint's chrome reduces the visible viewport unpredictably; prefer `%`
  of a known container or `dvh` where supported